To create a `SimplePagination` descendant and make it usable in a view XML descriptor in Jmix 2+ (FlowUI), you do the same as for any custom UI component:

1) create a Java subclass of `SimplePagination`
2) create an XML loader for it (extends `AbstractComponentLoader`)
3) register the component + loader via `ComponentRegistrationBuilder`
4) (optional) add XSD + Studio metadata so it appears nicely in Studio designer

Below is a working “skeleton” based on the official “Integrating into Jmix UI” approach (component XSD + loader + `ComponentRegistration`).  

## 1) Create a descendant of `SimplePagination`

```java
package com.company.app.component;

import io.jmix.flowui.component.pagination.SimplePagination;

public class MySimplePagination extends SimplePagination {

    public MySimplePagination() {
        super();
        // your customization here (styling, default flags, extra logic, etc.)
        setItemsPerPageVisible(true);
    }
}
```

If you only want to use it from Java (not from XML), you can just instantiate it and add to a layout — **no registration is required**. Registration is needed to support an XML element.

## 2) Create a component loader

Create a loader that will instantiate your component when Jmix parses the view XML.

```java
package com.company.app.component.loader;

import com.company.app.component.MySimplePagination;
import io.jmix.flowui.xml.layout.loader.AbstractComponentLoader;

public class MySimplePaginationLoader extends AbstractComponentLoader<MySimplePagination> {

    @Override
    protected MySimplePagination createComponent() {
        return factory.create(MySimplePagination.class);
    }

    @Override
    public void loadComponent() {
        // Load common attributes (id, visible, classNames, size, etc.) as needed.
        // Example: size attributes
        componentLoader().loadSizeAttributes(resultComponent, element);

        // If you need specific attributes, use helper methods from the base class, e.g.:
        // loadBoolean(element, "itemsPerPageVisible", resultComponent::setItemsPerPageVisible);

        // For SimplePagination-specific wiring like dataLoader="..." you must implement
        // the corresponding attribute handling here (resolve the referenced DataLoader and set it).
        //
        // (Exact attribute-to-API mapping depends on what you want to support in XML.)
    }
}
```

Important: the official docs show how to build loaders and register them, but they don’t provide a ready-made “inherit all `simplePagination` XML attributes automatically”. So in your loader you explicitly implement the attributes you want to support (including `dataLoader` if you need the same binding as standard `<simplePagination dataLoader="..."/>`).

## 3) Register the component and its loader in Spring

```java
package com.company.app.config;

import com.company.app.component.MySimplePagination;
import com.company.app.component.loader.MySimplePaginationLoader;
import io.jmix.flowui.kit.component.ComponentRegistration;
import io.jmix.flowui.kit.component.ComponentRegistrationBuilder;
import org.springframework.context.annotation.Bean;
import org.springframework.context.annotation.Configuration;

@Configuration
public class ComponentRegistrationConfiguration {

    @Bean
    public ComponentRegistration mySimplePagination() {
        return ComponentRegistrationBuilder.create(MySimplePagination.class)
                .withComponentLoader("mySimplePagination", MySimplePaginationLoader.class)
                .build();
    }
}
```

After that, Jmix knows that an XML element named `mySimplePagination` should be created using your loader.

## 4) Add XML namespace (XSD) to use it in view descriptors

Per the docs, you define your own namespace and XSD (example shown for a custom `slider` component). Conceptually it will look like:

```xml
<xs:schema xmlns="http://company.com/schema/app-ui-components"
           elementFormDefault="qualified"
           targetNamespace="http://company.com/schema/app-ui-components"
           xmlns:xs="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema"
           xmlns:layout="http://jmix.io/schema/flowui/layout">

    <xs:element name="mySimplePagination">
        <xs:complexType>
            <xs:complexContent>
                <xs:extension base="layout:baseComponent">
                    <!-- declare the XML attributes you want to support -->
                    <xs:attribute name="itemsPerPageVisible" type="xs:boolean"/>
                    <xs:attribute name="dataLoader" type="xs:string"/>
                    <xs:attributeGroup ref="layout:hasSize"/>
                </xs:extension>
            </xs:complexContent>
        </xs:complexType>
    </xs:element>

</xs:schema>
```

Then use it in the view XML:

```xml
<view xmlns="http://jmix.io/schema/flowui/view"
      xmlns:app="http://company.com/schema/app-ui-components">
    <layout>
        <app:mySimplePagination id="pagination"
                                itemsPerPageVisible="true"
                                dataLoader="usersDl"/>
    </layout>
</view>
```

## 5) (Optional) Make it appear in Jmix Studio palette

The docs describe adding `@StudioUiKit` + `@StudioComponent` metadata for Studio support. This is optional for runtime.

---

### One clarification (so I don’t guess the wrong level of detail)
Do you need your descendant to be used **as a new XML element** (like `<app:mySimplePagination/>`), or is it enough to use it **only from Java code** inside a view controller?

There are two common ways in Jmix 2+ to “save a `TextField` value for the current user”, depending on whether it’s **UI preference** (per view) or **business data** (part of the user profile).

## 1) Save as a per-user UI setting (recommended for UI preferences)
Use the `settings` facet and store your `TextField` value into user settings. These settings are stored per user in the `FLOWUI_USER_SETTINGS` table.

### View XML
```xml
<view xmlns="http://jmix.io/schema/flowui/view">
    <facets>
        <settings id="settings"/>
    </facets>

    <layout>
        <textField id="noteField" label="My note"/>
    </layout>
</view>
```

### View controller
```java
package com.company.app.view;

import io.jmix.flowui.component.textfield.TypedTextField;
import io.jmix.flowui.facet.SettingsFacet;
import io.jmix.flowui.view.Install;
import io.jmix.flowui.view.StandardView;
import io.jmix.flowui.view.ViewComponent;
import io.jmix.flowui.view.ViewController;
import io.jmix.flowui.view.ViewDescriptor;

import java.util.Optional;

@ViewController("my-view")
@ViewDescriptor("my-view.xml")
public class MyView extends StandardView {

    @ViewComponent
    private TypedTextField<String> noteField;

    @ViewComponent
    private SettingsFacet settings;

    @Install(to = "settings", subject = "applySettingsDelegate")
    private void applySettings(SettingsFacet.SettingsContext ctx) {
        settings.applySettings();

        Optional<String> value = ctx.getViewSettings().getString("noteField", "value");
        noteField.setValue(value.orElse(""));
    }

    @Install(to = "settings", subject = "saveSettingsDelegate")
    private void saveSettings(SettingsFacet.SettingsContext ctx) {
        ctx.getViewSettings().put("noteField", "value", noteField.getValue());
        settings.saveSettings();
    }
}
```

This makes the value “stick” for the current logged-in user and restores it when they reopen the view.

## 2) Save into the current user entity (recommended for profile data)
If the value is part of the user profile (e.g., “signature”, “default department”), add an attribute to your `User` entity and save it with `DataManager` for the currently authenticated user.

To show the correct code for this option, I need one detail: **do you want the value to be stored as a UI preference (per view) or as a field in the `User` entity (profile/business data)?**

To load children **only when a parent row is expanded** in Jmix Flow UI `TreeDataGrid`, use a **lazy hierarchical data provider** (Vaadin `HierarchicalDataProvider`). Then the grid will call your provider’s `fetchChildren()` / `getChildCount()` only for expanded nodes.

### 1) XML: declare `treeDataGrid` with `hierarchyProperty`
```xml
<view xmlns="http://jmix.io/schema/flowui/view">
    <layout>
        <treeDataGrid id="taskDataGrid"
                      metaClass="Task"
                      hierarchyProperty="parentTask"
                      width="100%"
                      minHeight="20em">
            <columns>
                <column property="name"/>
                <column property="dueDate"/>
                <column property="assignee"/>
            </columns>
        </treeDataGrid>
    </layout>
</view>
```

### 2) Controller: set a lazy `HierarchicalDataProvider`
This is based on the Jmix UI sample “TreeDataGrid with lazy nodes”.

```java
package com.company.app.view;

import com.vaadin.flow.data.provider.AbstractDataProvider;
import com.vaadin.flow.data.provider.hierarchy.HierarchicalDataProvider;
import com.vaadin.flow.data.provider.hierarchy.HierarchicalQuery;
import io.jmix.core.DataManager;
import io.jmix.core.LoadContext;
import io.jmix.core.Metadata;
import io.jmix.core.Sort;
import io.jmix.core.metamodel.model.MetaClass;
import io.jmix.flowui.component.grid.TreeDataGrid;
import io.jmix.flowui.view.InitEvent;
import io.jmix.flowui.view.StandardView;
import io.jmix.flowui.view.Subscribe;
import io.jmix.flowui.view.ViewComponent;
import org.springframework.beans.factory.annotation.Autowired;
import org.springframework.lang.Nullable;

import java.util.Collection;
import java.util.stream.Stream;

public class TasksTreeView extends StandardView {

    @ViewComponent
    private TreeDataGrid<Task> taskDataGrid;

    @Autowired
    private DataManager dataManager;
    @Autowired
    private Metadata metadata;

    @Subscribe
    public void onInit(InitEvent event) {
        taskDataGrid.setDataProvider(new TaskLazyTreeDataGridItems());
    }

    public class TaskLazyTreeDataGridItems extends AbstractDataProvider<Task, Void>
            implements HierarchicalDataProvider<Task, Void> {

        private Sort sort = Sort.UNSORTED;

        @Override
        public int getChildCount(HierarchicalQuery<Task, Void> query) {
            return Math.toIntExact(loadChildren(query).size());
        }

        @Override
        public Stream<Task> fetchChildren(HierarchicalQuery<Task, Void> query) {
            return loadChildren(query).stream();
        }

        private Collection<Task> loadChildren(HierarchicalQuery<Task, Void> query) {
            return dataManager.load(Task.class)
                    .query("select e from Task e where e.parentTask = :parent")
                    .parameter("parent", query.getParent())
                    .sort(sort)
                    .firstResult(query.getOffset())
                    .maxResults(query.getLimit())
                    .list();
        }

        @Override
        public boolean hasChildren(Task item) {
            LoadContext<Object> loadContext = new LoadContext<>(getEntityMetaClass())
                    .setQuery(new LoadContext.Query(
                            "select e from Task e where e.parentTask = :parent")
                            .setParameter("parent", item));

            return dataManager.getCount(loadContext) > 0;
        }

        private MetaClass getEntityMetaClass() {
            return metadata.getClass(Task.class);
        }
    }
}
```

### Notes
- With this approach, children are fetched **on expand**, not upfront.
- You don’t need to manually handle expand events for loading. The grid triggers provider calls automatically.
- If you *do* want side-effects (logging, notifications), you can additionally subscribe to `ExpandEvent` on the `treeDataGrid`, but loading should stay in the provider.

If you share your entity structure (the “parent” reference field name and how you want roots filtered), I can adapt the queries for “load roots only” + “load children on expand”.

If your `DataGrid` is bound to a `CollectionContainer`, you normally **don’t refresh the `DataGrid` directly**. You update the **container**, and the `DataGrid` redraws automatically because it listens to `CollectionContainer.CollectionChangeEvent`.

## 1) Add the saved instance to the container (recommended)
After `DataManager.save(entity)` use the *returned* instance and add/replace it in the container’s mutable items.

```java
@Autowired
private DataManager dataManager;

@ViewComponent
private CollectionContainer<Customer> customersDc;

private void createCustomer(Customer customer) {
    Customer saved = dataManager.save(customer);

    // triggers CollectionChangeEvent -> DataGrid updates automatically
    customersDc.getMutableItems().add(saved);
}
```

If you might be saving an existing item (or you just want “add or update” behavior), use `replaceItem()`:

```java
private void saveCustomer(Customer customer) {
    Customer saved = dataManager.save(customer);

    // replaces if exists by id, otherwise adds; also triggers DataGrid update
    customersDc.replaceItem(saved);
}
```

This pattern is also shown in the Flow UI inline editing example: after saving, the container is updated with `usersDc.replaceItem(savedUser)`.

## 2) If the grid is populated by a loader, reload it
If your list is loaded via a `CollectionLoader` (`...Dl`) and you want to re-query the DB (e.g., server-side sorting/filtering, calculated attributes, etc.), call:

```java
@ViewComponent
private CollectionLoader<Customer> customersDl;

private void reload() {
    customersDl.load();
}
```

## 3) If you use `DataContext`, merge the returned instance
When a view uses `DataContext` and you want the UI to continue working with the updated state returned from persistence, merge it into the `DataContext` (and add to the container if needed):

```java
@ViewComponent
private DataContext dataContext;

private void saveAndAttach(Customer customer) {
    Customer saved = dataManager.save(customer);
    Customer tracked = dataContext.merge(saved);

    customersDc.replaceItem(tracked);
}
```

### Which option should you use?
- **Just created/saved something and want it to appear immediately**: `customersDc.getMutableItems().add(saved)` or `customersDc.replaceItem(saved)`.
- **Need a full refresh from DB**: `customersDl.load()`.
- **View tracks changes with `DataContext`**: `dataContext.merge(saved)` + update container.

If you share how your view is set up (is the loader `readOnly="true"`? do you have `<data>` / `DataContext`?), I can suggest the exact best variant.
